# jemdoc: menu{MENU}{project.html}
== Projects

=== Adaptive Planner Parameter Learning from Reinforcement (APPLR)

{{<div align="left">
<img src="photos/applr.png" alt="research" height="200" width="300">
<br>
</div>}}
*Description*\n
Classical navigation systems typically operate using a fixed set of hand-picked parameters (e.g. maximum speed, sampling rate, inflation radius, etc.) and require heavy expert re-tuning in order to work in new environments. To mitigate this requirement, we introduce APPLR, Adaptive Planner Parameter Learning from Reinforcement, which allows existing navigation systems to adapt to new scenarios by using a parameter selection scheme discovered via reinforcement learning (RL) in a wide variety of simulation environments. We evaluate APPLR on a robot in both simulated and physical experiments, and show that it can outperform both a fixed set of hand-tuned parameters and also a dynamic parameter tuning scheme learned from human demonstration.\n
\n*My contributions*\n
- Developed an OpenAI gym environment that simulates mobile robot navigation from ROS Gazebo simulation.
- Implemented a complete pipeline for training the model using Twin Delayed Deep Deterministic (TD3) algorithm.
- Applied clustering computing to parallelize the acting processes of the actor-critic framework and reduced the training time byten times.

=== Lifelong Learning Machine (L2M) — Scavenger Hunt Service Robot

{{<div align="left">
<img src="photos/sh.png" alt="research" height="230" width="575">
<br>
</div>}}
*Description*\n
The project targeted an optimization problem that minimizes traveling distance for fetching a list of random objects in the environment using a service robot. The problem is formulated  as  a  variation  of  the  NP-hard  stochastictraveling  purchaser  problem. We investigate the performance of several solution algorithmsfor  the  SH  problem,  both  in  simulation  and  on  a  real  mobilerobot. We use Reinforcement Learning (RL) to train an agentto  plan  a  minimal  cost  path,  and  show  that  the  RL  agentcan outperform a range of heuristic algorithms, achieving nearoptimal  performance. Lifelong learning algorithms were integrated to solve the problem under the lifelong learning setting that changes the tasks and environments continuously.\n
\n*My contributions*\n
- Modeled the Scavenger Hunt as a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP) and trained a RL policy using DeepQ-network (DQN) algorithm with belief state of distribution map as the observation.
- Developed a core OpenAI gym environment from Habitat AI simulator.
- Collaborated with a large group of researchers from different universities via Zoom meetings.

=== Smartphone-based Foreground Speech Detection

{{<div align="left">
<img src="photos/smartphone.png" alt="research" height="150" width="470">
<br>
</div>}}
*Description*\n
In this project, we explore the opportunity of automatically detecting the wearer’s foreground speech in naturalistic domestic environments by using a commodity smartwatch. We provide in-depth quantitative evaluations of the performance based on field recordings collected from 11 groups of participants in their home and show the feasibility of foreground speech detection by using only high-level acoustic-based and embedding-based input features.\n
\n*My contributions*\n
- Set up the prototype that collected and processed the audio data from smartphones and trained deep learning models withdifferent architectures (CNN, CNNLSTM, VGG-slimmer) to detect the foreground speech from the audio
- Developed a model-free detection method that utilizes the cosine similarity of embedding features. The simple model-freemethod showed almost the same performance to those trained models.
